				<outline text="Okay here's an idea. I'm going to be in NYC much of July. Who wants to go to a Mets game?" created="Wed, 30 Jun 2004 01:47:47 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.outliners.com/discuss/msgReader$1990&quot;&gt;Outliners.com poster&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I am re-posting this which was posted just prior to the whatever-it-was-that-happened of outliners.com.&quot; It got knocked off the air by the problems with weblogs.com, and the resulting flood of traffic. " created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 22:29:12 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.metafilter.com/mefi/34015#693992&quot;&gt;Metafilter thread&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Pompous sociopath or not, you've got to admit, he pretty much has us pegged.&quot;" created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 22:27:16 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/29/dietpepsi.gif&quot; width=&quot;45&quot; height=&quot;78&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named dietpepsi.gif&quot;&gt;BTW, the topic of discussion on Metafilter has meandered into a quote of mine from a MF thread in Y2K where I introduced myself by saying everyone there is full of shit. I'm afraid they might have misunderstood me. All my &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/crimson1/whatIsFriendship#whenFriendsAreFullOfShit&quot;&gt;friends&lt;/a&gt; are full of shit at one time or another. All of yours are too. I did a search of the term on this weblog and came up with some good &lt;a href=&quot;http://archive.scripting.com/search/default?q=full+of+shit&quot;&gt;hits&lt;/a&gt;. Some people are proud to be full of shit (these are people I admire, like Scoble) and then some people will take offense if you say they're full of shit (names withheld). My attitude is that if you say I'm full of shit that's a sign of respect, because you're acknowledging that I exist. " created="Wed, 30 Jun 2004 01:33:24 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/crimson1/whatIsFriendship#backToTheGreatVaVaVoom&quot;&gt;9/20/03&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;There's little point arguing about whether I'm full of shit or not. I am. It's demonstrable.&quot;" created="Wed, 30 Jun 2004 01:40:40 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.docuverse.com/blog/donpark/EntryViewPage.aspx?guid=922&quot;&gt;See&lt;/a&gt;, Don Park says I'm full of shit, and I point to him. There's some kind of invisible brotherhood between Koreans and NY Jews. Not sure what it is, but we get along in some basic way that's very mysterious." created="Wed, 30 Jun 2004 01:58:06 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://weblog.siliconvalley.com/column/dangillmor/archives/010540.shtml&quot;&gt;Dan Gillmor reports&lt;/a&gt; on Apple's announcements." created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 16:42:07 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/29/jfk.gif&quot; width=&quot;52&quot; height=&quot;69&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named jfk.gif&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.oreillynet.com/pub/wlg/5132&quot;&gt;I like William Grosso&lt;/a&gt; and point to him often, at least in part because he might be the only O'Reilly author who reads my site, but every time I link to him, I'm &lt;a href=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/29/somethingMissing.gif&quot;&gt;reminded&lt;/a&gt; that O'Reilly doesn't support RSS 2.0. On Sunday I &lt;a href=&quot;http://archive.scripting.com/2004/06/26#When:4:54:45PM&quot;&gt;asked&lt;/a&gt; &quot;What are you going to do help the tech-weblog world get back on its feet?&quot; One thing O'Reilly (the company) could do is accept that RSS 2.0 is here to stay, and help to close the wounds that keep us all from working together. &quot;Ask not what the Internet can do for you, ask what you can do for the Internet.&quot;" created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 16:01:43 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Grosso is great because he notices irony in software. For example, yesterday he found out about Apple's RSS reader that might crowd NetNewsWire, by reading about it in NetNewsWire. The software is fair, and has no ego. &quot;There's something spiritual about computers,&quot; &lt;a href=&quot;http://davenet.scripting.com/1997/05/07/Programmers&quot;&gt;1997&lt;/a&gt;." created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 16:19:04 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="News.Com: &lt;a href=&quot;http://news.com.com/When+standards+don%27t+apply/2100-1013_3-5250780.html?part=rss&amp;tag=5250780&amp;subj=news.1013.5&quot;&gt;When standards don't apply&lt;/a&gt;. &quot;A growing roster of de facto standards is testing the need for bureaucratic agencies and design-by-committee technologies.&quot;" created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 11:57:11 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Gary Lerhaupt writes: \&quot;Etree.org has converted their &lt;a href=&quot;http://bt.etree.org/rss/bt_etree_org.rdf&quot;&gt;RSS feed&lt;/a&gt; to support BitTorrent enclosures.  Etree is an awesome repository of legal concerts (Phish, Grateful Dead, etc).  I'm downloading my last Phish show from my TV as we speak.\&quot;" created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 13:34:50 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scottedelman.com/worldcon2003_2.html&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/29/finger.jpg&quot; width=&quot;45&quot; height=&quot;82&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named finger.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;News.Com got it right. The current standards organizations have the wrong strategy, they get in the way of progress instead of fostering it. After years of studying this, I now think we need a new standards organization that adopts de facto standards, like BitTorrent and RSS, OPML, XML-RPC, the ones with market momentum, that have proven their value. The current SO's form committees and bureaucracies, that's their purpose it seems, and by the time they're ready with a format or protocol, their proposal is too complex and too late. " created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 13:35:32 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://danbricklin.com/log/2004_06_29.htm&quot;&gt;Dan Bricklin&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I've just posted the 1.0 version of my ListGarden RSS Generator Program.&quot;" created="Tue, 29 Jun 2004 15:16:13 GMT" type="outline"/>
