			<outline text="June 28" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.apple.com/macosx/tiger/&quot;&gt;Apple&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Safari RSS, a new version of Apple’s innovative web browser that provides instant access to the most current RSS information on the web.&quot;" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 19:08:53 GMT" name="aHrefhttpwwwapplecommacosxtigerappleaSafariRssANewVersionOfApplesInnovativeWebBrowserThatProvidesInstantAccessToTheMostCurrentRssInformationOnTheWeb" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Apple also announced &lt;a href=&quot;http://biz.yahoo.com/prnews/040628/sfm106_1.html&quot;&gt;Tiger Server&lt;/a&gt;, which includes David Czarnecki's &lt;a href=&quot;http://wiki.blojsom.com/wiki/display/blojsom/About+blojsom&quot;&gt;Blojsom&lt;/a&gt; weblog CMS bundled, an XML-RPC &lt;a href=&quot;http://wiki.blojsom.com/wiki/display/blojsom/XML-RPC&quot;&gt;interface&lt;/a&gt;, as well as publishing content in RSS." created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 19:26:06 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/28/apple.gif&quot; width=&quot;65&quot; height=&quot;78&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named apple.gif&quot;&gt;Here's a really cool &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.apple.com/macosx/tiger/theater/safari.html&quot;&gt;demo&lt;/a&gt; of their RSS reader. Based on squinting at this demo, it appears they did it right. It's not three-pane, it's one panel, with the items displayed, from all your feeds, in reverse chronologic order. This is the most efficient way to read for the user. A lot of designers think RSS readers should work just like mail apps, but that's too inefficient. With mail you need to keep spam and mail list content segregated. For news, you need a different interface. I've been saying it for years, the Apple designers apparently didn't get sucked into the design mistake so many have. One thing I wish Apple had done differently is respect the white-on-orange &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/xml.gif&quot;&gt;icon&lt;/a&gt;. Such a small thing, but so important. One would think Apple, of all, would understand the value of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.asktog.com/basics/firstPrinciples.html#consistency&quot;&gt;consistent&lt;/a&gt; user interface." created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 20:00:08 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://davenet.scripting.com/1999/05/24/editThisPage&quot;&gt;5/24/99&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Let's study User Interface again.&quot;" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 20:18:06 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="And thus begins the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.inessential.com/2004/06/28.php&quot;&gt;developer dance&lt;/a&gt;, how this is good for the market, etc. I expect we'll be hearing a lot of this, first among Mac developers, and then inevitably, among Windows developers. I don't know what's going to happen. Maybe the few cross-platform aggregators or centralized aggregators will be what's left standing, although Yahoo and MSN and Google, at least one of them must be preparing a competent aggregator or RSS-based blogging tool (Google's still doesn't support RSS.) With Apple bundling a blogging back-end, that market changes too, don't miss that. What does Microsoft have planned here? I'm sure there are companies that would happily sell them what they need to enter the market quickly. " created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 19:42:41 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Now a commercial message. As of Thursday I've got lots of free time. I am available for consulting on strategies related to RSS, blogging, aggregators, etc. I'm not cheap, but you'll get your money's worth. &quot;;-&gt;&quot;" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 19:48:44 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bryanbell.com/2004/06/28#a1055&quot;&gt;Bryan Bell has notes&lt;/a&gt; from MacRumors about the RSS capabilities of Safari. Apparently you can search the contents of the feeds. This is something Steve Gillmor has been asking for, for ages. Feedster on the Desktop. Of course it can only search the feeds you're subscribed to. Already got a call from a reporter wanting to know if Microsoft can be far behind. Yeah, probably not too far behind. " created="Mon, 28 Jun 2004 18:56:45 GMT" type="outline"/>
