				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.pbs.org/cringely/pulpit/pulpit20040610.html&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/11/cole.jpg&quot; width=&quot;55&quot; height=&quot;51&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named cole.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.pbs.org/cringely/pulpit/pulpit20040610.html&quot;&gt;Cringely&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I give credit to Dave Winer of Userland Software for inventing web logging, and I think the idea then was to publish, to share your thoughts with everyone else. But most people's thoughts aren't really worth sharing. Most web logs are little more than lists of annotated bookmarks and the value of those bookmarks can probably be best derived through a web aggregator, in which case people would be writing not to be read but to be counted, which isn't nearly as much fun.&quot;" created="Fri, 11 Jun 2004 18:05:04 GMT" type="outline"/>
