				<outline text="Standards nazis" created="Tue, 08 Jun 2004 12:35:16 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/08/soupNazi.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/08/naziSmall.jpg&quot; width=&quot;95&quot; height=&quot;201&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;No soup for you!&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;When we were developing SOAP in 1998 and 1999, another group was working on &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.webdav.org/&quot;&gt;WebDAV&lt;/a&gt;. SOAP was higher level, you could create a toolkit that mapped SOAP calls on the procedure-calling mechanism in any scripting system. I never understood WebDAV, so I hired a smart young &lt;a href=&quot;http://wmf.editthispage.com/&quot;&gt;guy&lt;/a&gt; to implement it for UserLand (he works at IBM now). Never happened. " created="Tue, 08 Jun 2004 12:29:15 GMT"/>
					<outline text="There were three groups at Microsoft, one working on WebDAV, another working with Allaire on WDDX, and a third working on SOAP. Anyway, if this were a horror movie, we'd say They're baaaaack, about the WebDAV folk. Amazingly, they're talking about retrofitting weblog APIs to be part of WebDAV. What an stunningly stupid step backwards. " created="Tue, 08 Jun 2004 12:41:05 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Some corporate programmers are amazing that way, rapidly driving off the cliff to get off the high road and quickly get mired in the mud. Glad I'm not involved in that debate. Eventually even SOAP got mired, so we stuck with XML-RPC. Oh for the good old days, when we could ratify a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.xmlrpc.com/directory/1568/bloggingApis/~1568/services/pyraLabsblogger~&quot;&gt;standard&lt;/a&gt; proposed &lt;a href=&quot;http://archive.scripting.com/search/default?q=blogger+api&quot;&gt;by Evan&lt;/a&gt; in a matter of hours. Look at all the overhead that's come into it. Blogging as a technical art, may almost be over, the standards nazis are taking over." created="Tue, 08 Jun 2004 12:41:43 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
