			<outline text="June 4" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/2004/06/04#a553&quot;&gt;A proposed clarification&lt;/a&gt; for the RSS 2.0 spec is ready for review. If there aren't any deal-stoppers, we'll make the changes early next week. Thanks to Nick Bradbury for help with the &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/encodingDescriptions&quot;&gt;encoding examples&lt;/a&gt; and to Brent Simmons, Greg Reinacker, Jake Savin, Dare Obasanjo and Matt Mullenweg for help working out this proposed clarification." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 17:12:43 GMT" name="" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://news.com.com/Google+buys+e-mail+software+company/2100-1024_3-5227110.html?part=rss&amp;tag=feed&amp;subj=news&quot;&gt;News.Com&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Search giant Google, which is building up its Web-based messaging services, has quietly acquired an e-mail software company.&quot;" created="Sat, 05 Jun 2004 01:43:51 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.infoworld.com/article/04/06/04/HNnodecision_1.html?source=rss&amp;url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/04/06/04/HNnodecision_1.html&quot;&gt;InfoWorld&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Contrary to published reports, Sun Microsystems Inc. has not made a decision as to whether or not to release its Java platform under an open source software license, company executives said on Friday.&quot;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 20:45:57 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.crabapples.net/artwork/misc/snOnTheRoad.jpg&quot;&gt;Rob Fahrni misses&lt;/a&gt; the Scripting News cactus. &quot;When I saw this picture, from your drive across the country, I knew it was the perfect place!&quot;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 16:18:52 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/laptopImages/07/21/RSSGreenOnWhite.gif&quot; width=&quot;65&quot; height=&quot;59&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;Love RSS.&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bestkungfu.com/archive/?id=492&quot;&gt;The W3C made&lt;/a&gt; a pitch for Atom, but according to Matt May &quot;we generally failed to, as they say, win hearts and minds.&quot; If Atom turns them down, as it appears they will, the W3C can &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss#licenseAndAuthorship&quot;&gt;start with RSS&lt;/a&gt;, which has a much larger installed base, is better-known and has a five-year head-start. It's the front-runner by a wide margin. Anyway, I'm still in Boston through the end of the month, which is right down the &lt;a href=&quot;http://maps.yahoo.com/maps_result?ed=A0wR7ep_0To3_nMH17ucaEUqsT_nVR0xqBXEk34-&amp;csz=cambridge%2Cma&amp;country=us&amp;new=1&amp;name=&amp;qty=&quot;&gt;street&lt;/a&gt; from the W3C. They &lt;i&gt;might&lt;/i&gt; want to &lt;i&gt;try&lt;/i&gt; to talk with me about this. I have strong opinions, true, but I don't bite. &quot;;-&gt;&quot;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 12:42:32 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="If you want the W3C to help RSS, &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/dave/profiles/sendMail?usernum=1&amp;referer=http://www.scripting.com/&quot;&gt;send me an email&lt;/a&gt;, and let me know if it's okay to publish it. Not sure exactly what I can do with the emails, but it couldn't hurt. Be sure to say what your interest is, if you work at a tech company, are a blogger, publisher, tool or aggregator developer, or are a user of any or all of the above. " category="/Dave/Scripting News" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 13:25:15 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/crimson1/rssAtW3C&quot;&gt;Comments&lt;/a&gt; I've received, in reverse-chronologic order." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 16:36:03 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.docuverse.com/blog/donpark/EntryViewPage.aspx?guid=39b08c7c-6581-4afa-a4da-9e8b2d2f2cab&quot;&gt;Don Park thinks&lt;/a&gt; RSS at the W3C makes sense." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 15:30:54 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://ojr.org/ojr/technology/1086293132.php&quot;&gt;OJR&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I haven't been to the New York Times home page in years and yet I read 20 articles a day in the New York Times,&quot;" category="/Technology/Formats and Protocols/RSS" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 12:32:59 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.wired.com/news/business/0,1367,63707,00.html&quot;&gt;Wired&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I'm amazed that this patent was filed so late and was approved. It's a double-click.&quot; " created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 10:25:27 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.technology.gov/Medal/2000/photos/Engelbart_Shavers_Minetaphoto2.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/04/engelbart.jpg&quot; width=&quot;45&quot; height=&quot;56&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named engelbart.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://sloan.stanford.edu/MouseSite/1968Demo.html&quot;&gt;The Demo&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;On December 9, 1968, Douglas C. Engelbart and the group of 17 researchers working with him in the Augmentation Research Center at Stanford Research Institute in Menlo Park, CA, presented a 90-minute live public demonstration of the online system, NLS, they had been working on since 1962.&quot;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 10:48:55 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://davenet.scripting.com/2000/07/24/doYouKnowStepenKing&quot;&gt;7/24/00&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Imagine if you couldn't write a story because Dean Koontz had already written it. What if the idea were as basic as Boy Meets Girl? That's what's going on in another creative space, software.&quot;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 10:41:15 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="We talked about the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.reallysimplesyndication.com/&quot;&gt;Really Simple Syndication&lt;/a&gt; site at last night's meeting at Berkman. We're going start a project to create a simple catalog, with brief descriptions, of all the aggregators. Lisa Williams and Shimon Rura are going to work with me on this." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 10:26:44 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;i&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/thursdaymeetings/2004/06/03#a99&quot;&gt;We won't&lt;/a&gt; have a meeting next Thursday, June 10, because it's commencement day at Harvard.&lt;/i&gt;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 10:37:38 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 3" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="OJR: &lt;a href=&quot;http://ojr.org/ojr/technology/1086293132.php&quot;&gt;RSS Feeds Can Build Web Traffic, But..&lt;/a&gt;" created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 00:36:19 GMT" name="ojrAHrefhttpojrorgojrtechnology1086293132phprssFeedsCanBuildWebTrafficButa" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.engadget.com/entry/4610516638437140/&quot;&gt;Engadget&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Damn, Phillip, you have enough iPods yet?&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 21:57:30 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/03/technology/circuits/03diar.html?ex=1401681600&amp;en=09fa1af94f8995db&amp;ei=5007&amp;partner=USERLAND&quot;&gt;Another NY Times bit&lt;/a&gt; about R.S.S. Scroll down to &quot;Simple Charity.&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 18:33:37 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.fantasywaistcoats.co.uk/flags.shtml&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/03/unionJackVest.gif&quot; width=&quot;85&quot; height=&quot;127&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named unionJackVest.gif&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;I finally got a chance to read the WSJ article about RSS. They gave me authorship credit for the format, appropriately. I know how long they worked on the story, so it's much appreciated. The Guardian, in a deeply flawed &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.guardian.co.uk/online/story/0,3605,1171185,00.html&quot;&gt;article&lt;/a&gt;, said something very different about the origins of RSS. One wonders how they would react if I claimed to write an article of theirs that made a big difference in the world. You launch so many ideas, when one succeeds, it's nice to get credit for it. Anyway, there's no doubt why one got the story right and one didn't. The WSJ assigned a reporter, and he thoroughly researched it. The Guardian assigned a politician, and he wrote an ad for his cause, and they ran it as a news article. I hear that journalism works differently in the UK. Damn right about that. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 18:34:19 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="CIA &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/0604/p25s01-uspo.html&quot;&gt;Director&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,645382,00.html&quot;&gt;George&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/3774089.stm&quot;&gt;Tenet&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://news.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2004/06/03/uten.xml&quot;&gt;resigned&lt;/a&gt;. Who's next?" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 14:43:36 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://jrobb.mindplex.org/2004/06/03.html#a4833&quot;&gt;John Robb's instant&lt;/a&gt; analysis of the Tenet departure." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 15:47:31 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Buy or sell signal for stocks? Bonds? Gold? Oil? Tech?" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 15:48:23 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://skiplombardi.com/&quot;&gt;Skip's Italian Food Blog&lt;/a&gt;." created="Fri, 04 Jun 2004 00:34:00 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="The &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/03/technology/circuits/03basi.html?ex=1401681600&amp;en=1a98ebe9b0669206&amp;ei=5007&amp;partner=USERLAND&quot;&gt;article&lt;/a&gt; about R.S.S. in the N.Y. T.I.M.E.S. &lt;I&gt;does&lt;/i&gt; mention their feeds (I read too quickly) but it doesn't &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/directory/5/feeds/newYorkTimes&quot;&gt;point&lt;/a&gt; to them. &quot;;-&gt;&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 15:42:06 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://trademark.blog.us/blog/2004/06/03.html#a1218&quot;&gt;Martin Schwimmer&lt;/a&gt; doesn't know how he got hit by adware." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 15:45:37 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://weblog.burningbird.net/archives/2004/06/02/fish-swimming-the-wrong-way/&quot;&gt;Burningbird&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;I can’t be the only person who is uncomfortable with the premise behind Spirit of America.&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 13:48:32 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gizmodo.com/archives/argus-sub50-digital-cameras-reach-the-stores-015602.php&quot;&gt;Gizmodo reports&lt;/a&gt; on a sub-$50 digital camera you can buy at Walmart." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:09:22 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Competitors" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:43:02 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/03/esther.jpg&quot; width=&quot;94&quot; height=&quot;240&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named esther.jpg&quot;&gt;In 1991, I wrote a &lt;a href=&quot;http://davenet.scripting.com/1995/01/04/demoingsoftwareforfunprofi&quot;&gt;training manual&lt;/a&gt; for Stewart Alsop's Demo conference (it's now Chris Shipley's show) that coached software developers on how to demo software. The piece is a little dated, using software buzzwords of the time, but the basic ideas never go out of date. Focus on comprehension, find the memorable feature, know that your prospect isn't as interested in your software as you are, practice your demo with friends, never use new software in your demos, and watch out for competitors who try to derail your pitch." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:41:40 GMT"/>
					<outline text="In the last few days we wasted way too much time because of a curveball thrown by a couple of really nasty competitors. It's true, we're competing over something that doesn't make money, a format, but as they say in academia, the less there is at stake, the more vicious the competiton, or something like that. I've been Mr Naive about this. " created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:44:56 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I'm going to work with users, they seem to appreciate what I do. The techies and developers, until further notice, are bums. I almost want to say I hate what the technology industry has become, but when has it been anything but back-stabbing, low-road bullshit. We could be so damned powerful if we just worked together, but that clearly isn't what's going on." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:49:09 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://sethgodin.typepad.com/seths_blog/2004/05/on_thinking_big.html&quot;&gt;Seth Godin&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;It's sad to see someone choosing to be stuck.&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 13:17:20 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Competition can be good" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:55:33 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I've said many times, competitors can be your best teachers. They're perfect mirrors, look at a competitor and you can get an idea of what people see when they look at you. A good competitor knows you as well as anyone else, and vice versa." created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 11:55:39 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I point to the competition when they're playing reasonably fair. It's not always good for business, but I assume our readers are smart, and that they'll make the right decision given all the facts. And by assuming readers are smart, we attract smart readers. " created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 11:36:53 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="June 2" created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.reallysimplesyndication.com/2004/06/02#a76&quot;&gt;Really Simple Syndication&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Dave, how I can explain to my large media corporation higher-ups why it's not a bad thing that they lose traffic if their readers are using our RSS feeds instead of visiting the site?&quot;" category="/Technology/Formats and Protocols/RSS" created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 14:35:54 GMT" name="aHrefhttpwwwreallysimplesyndicationcom20040602a76reallySimpleSyndicationaDaveHowICanExplainToMyLargeMediaCorporationHigherupsWhyItsNotABadThingThatTheyLoseTrafficIfTheirReadersAreUsingOurRssFeedsInsteadOfVisitingTheSite" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/03/technology/circuits/03basi.html?ex=1401681600&amp;en=1a98ebe9b0669206&amp;ei=5007&amp;partner=USERLAND&quot;&gt;A milestone&lt;/a&gt;, the first NY Times article about RSS. It's not the greatest or most insightful piece. They spell it funny, with periods after each of the letters. But it's the paper of record, so I guess now we can say it's officially happened. Funny that they didn't mention &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/directory/5/feeds/newYorkTimes&quot;&gt;their&lt;/a&gt; own feeds. &quot;;-&gt;&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 03:27:37 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gizmodo.com/archives/music-industry-drm-firms-want-you-to-pay-to-restrict-your-fair-use-015576.php&quot;&gt;Gizmodo&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;There's an ethical dissonance between trying to support the artists you like and the industry you hate (and who hates you).&quot;" created="Thu, 03 Jun 2004 00:20:08 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sixflags.com/index.asp&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/02/sixFlagsDancer.jpg&quot; width=&quot;65&quot; height=&quot;70&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named sixFlagsDancer.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Six Flags has the greatest TV commercial on the air. It's hauntingly good. When it came on during one of my TiVO-recorded programs I watched it repeatedly, and then watched it in slow motion to see how they did it. Debunks the theory that people skip commercials with DVR's, quite the opposite, if your ad is good enough I'll watch it over and over. And this is one smart company. I went to their &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sixflags.com/index.asp&quot;&gt;website&lt;/a&gt;, and there in big spot in the middle of the page it says &quot;Click to see our new commercial.&quot; And so I did. Happily, it's the same one that was so mesmerizing on TV, and it's just as amazing &lt;a href=&quot;mms://streams.sixflags.com/SFMR6PDA&quot;&gt;on the Web&lt;/a&gt;." created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 17:30:58 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Now wouldn't it be great if Taco Bell put all their &lt;a href=&quot;http://davenet.scripting.com/1998/05/06/yoQuieroScriptingNews&quot;&gt;dog commercials&lt;/a&gt; on the Web. Yo quiero Taco Bell commercials!" created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 18:29:27 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Hey thanks to &lt;a href=&quot;http://dir.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Data_Formats/XML__eXtensible_Markup_Language_/RSS/&quot;&gt;Yahoo&lt;/a&gt; for the great &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.reallysimplesyndication.com/pictures/viewer$87&quot;&gt;link&lt;/a&gt; to the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.reallysimplesyndication.com/&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/images/archiveScriptingCom/2004/06/02/new2.gif&quot; width=&quot;28&quot; height=&quot;11&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named new2.gif&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; site!" created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 17:07:51 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://radio.weblogs.com/0001011/2004/06/02.html#a7665&quot;&gt;Scoble is hosting&lt;/a&gt; a blogger's dinner in NYC on June 16. " created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 16:45:52 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Louisville doctors are considering &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.cnn.com/2004/TECH/science/05/26/face.transplant/&quot;&gt;face transplants&lt;/a&gt;. " created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 16:48:53 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.blognewsnetwork.com/members/0000001/2004/06/02.html#a5775&quot;&gt;Adam Curry reviews&lt;/a&gt; the Nucleus BitTorrent aggregator." created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 15:14:30 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bensinclair.com/syndication/&quot;&gt;Ben Sinclair&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;In response to Dave Winer's RSS-specific weblog for users, I've created my own Syndication for Users weblog.&quot;" created="Wed, 02 Jun 2004 11:30:45 GMT" type="outline"/>
